  <mads:note type="source">LC data base, 4/17/91 (hdg.: Philo, of Byzantium)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Der kleine Pauly (Philon von Byzanz)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Oxford classical dict., 1970 (Philon of Byzantium, writer on technology,
    late 3rd cent. B.C.)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Seyffert, O. Dict. of classical antiq., 1956 (Philo, of Byzantium, mechanician, 
    2nd cent. B.C.)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">His Le livre des appareils pneumatiques et des machines hydrauliques, 1903: t.p. (Philon de
    Byzance)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Philo of Byzantium, Greek mechanic who supposedly lived shortly after Ctesibius
    .... therefore probably at the beginning of the 2nd cent. BC [3.41, 7.13f.  5.vol. 2, 300f.]. He wrote a work on 
    mechanics (Μηχανικὴ σύνταξις/Mēchanikḕ sýntaxis) in 9 volumes of which volume 4 as well as excerpts from volumes 7 and 8 (= volume 5 in old editions)
    are preserved in Greek translations volume 5 is preserved in Arabic ( and partly in a Latin translation from the Arabic). 
    Volume 4 (title: Βελοποιικά/Belopoiiká, 'The Manufacture of Cannons' edition: [8. part 1]
    edition and German translation: [1]) gives very detailed instructions about how to build cannons (see the illustrations
    in [1. plate 3-8]). Volume 5 (Πνευματικά/Pneumatiká, 'Pneumatics'
    English translation and edition of the Latin translation ..." from Folkerts, Menso (Munich). "Philo." 
    Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and
    Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2011. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 22 September 2011</mads:note>
